<i>♪ Sink back into the o... ♪</i>

02:24.227 --> 02:24.895
<i>♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪</i>

02:24.978 --> 02:27.522
<i>♪ Sink back into the o... ♪</i>

02:27.606 --> 02:29.066
<i>♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪</i>

02:29.149 --> 02:31.318
<i>♪ Sink back</i>
<i>into the ocean ♪</i>

03:01.306 --> 03:04.601
[Noah]
<i>And five, six, seven, eight.</i>

03:04.685 --> 03:05.769
<i>[The Waterboys' "The Whole</i>
<i>of the Moon" playing]</i>

03:05.852 --> 03:09.898
<i>♪♪♪</i>

03:09.981 --> 03:11.942
[Colin]
What's the next move?

03:12.025 --> 03:14.361
[indistinct chatter]

03:20.075 --> 03:21.785
[Noah]
You ready?

03:21.868 --> 03:23.620
And pizza arms.

03:23.704 --> 03:25.372
<i>‐♪</i> I pictured a rainbow... ♪
‐Pizzas.

03:25.455 --> 03:27.124
Pi... like a pizza.
Yeah.

03:27.207 --> 03:28.583
Okay, turn.

03:28.667 --> 03:29.793
‐Spin. And spin.
‐Hey.

03:29.876 --> 03:33.130
Spin. Two, three, four.

03:33.213 --> 03:33.630
Ride the tractor.

03:33.713 --> 03:36.591
<i>♪♪♪</i>

03:36.675 --> 03:37.759
[indistinct chatter]

03:37.843 --> 03:40.470
Kick the puppy.

03:40.554 --> 03:42.264
Kick the puppy
with your right foot, Trevor.

03:42.347 --> 03:44.266
‐[Trevor] Stacey, really?
‐Kick the puppy.

03:44.349 --> 03:44.724
‐[grunting, groaning]
‐Kick‐‐

03:44.808 --> 03:47.018
Okay. Sorry.

03:47.102 --> 03:47.853
‐Sorry, sorry.
‐Stop, stop.

03:47.936 --> 03:50.147
‐Stop.
<i>‐[song stops]</i>

03:50.230 --> 03:51.982
Okay, let's start again.
Back to one.

03:52.065 --> 03:54.609
Trevor, you kick the puppy
with your right foot.

03:54.693 --> 03:55.485
"Kick the puppy"?

03:55.569 --> 03:56.445
‐Yes.
‐Dad,

03:56.528 --> 03:57.612
what the fuck does
"ride the tractor" mean?

03:57.696 --> 03:59.573
Martin, I've told you
three times.

03:59.656 --> 04:02.284
This, okay? This is
ride the tractor, okay?

04:02.367 --> 04:04.661
Ride the tractor.
Kick the puppy. All right?

04:04.744 --> 04:08.039
It's easy. Okay?

04:08.123 --> 04:09.124
Come on, everyone.

04:09.207 --> 04:10.709
Your sister wants
a flash dance for her wedding‐‐

04:10.792 --> 04:11.918
Flash mob.

04:12.002 --> 04:13.128
A flash mob for her wedding.

04:13.211 --> 04:13.753
And that's what she's gonna get,
okay?

04:13.837 --> 04:14.713
So come on.

04:14.796 --> 04:15.881
Let's go again.

04:15.964 --> 04:19.468
Everyone back
to one.

04:19.801 --> 04:21.845
Okay,

04:21.928 --> 04:22.554
once more with feeling.

04:22.637 --> 04:24.139
And, remember, you're happy!

04:24.222 --> 04:25.849
Your sister's getting married!

04:25.932 --> 04:27.851
So, smile.

04:27.934 --> 04:29.811
‐Okay. Let's go.
<i>‐[song playing]</i>

04:29.895 --> 04:31.188
‐Hey.
‐Oh, hey.

04:31.271 --> 04:32.230
‐How's it going?
<i>‐[song stops]</i>

04:32.314 --> 04:35.192
It's going great.
It's going great.

04:35.275 --> 04:36.693
‐It's going great.
‐[Stacey] Mom, come on.

04:36.777 --> 04:37.819
Get in.

04:37.903 --> 04:40.363
I can't.
I'm the videographer.

04:40.447 --> 04:43.617
‐Show me what you got.
‐Yeah, well, it's not...

04:43.700 --> 04:45.327
it's not, uh...
it's not perfect yet. It's not‐‐

04:45.410 --> 04:46.286
‐I'll be kind.
‐We're still‐still developing.

04:46.369 --> 04:49.164
‐Just show me.
‐[Trevor] Yeah, Dad,

04:49.247 --> 04:50.499
are we doing this or what?
It's fucking freezing.

04:53.919 --> 04:55.587
Yes, Trevor. Let's go.

04:55.670 --> 04:58.340
Ready?

04:58.423 --> 05:01.343
Five, six, seven, eight!

05:01.426 --> 05:02.844
<i>["The Whole of the Moon"</i>
<i>playing]</i>

05:02.928 --> 05:06.056
<i>♪♪♪</i>

05:20.362 --> 05:22.447
<i>♪ I pictured a rainbow ♪</i>

05:22.531 --> 05:25.200
[Noah]
Nice.

05:25.283 --> 05:28.036
<i>♪ You held it in your hands ♪</i>

05:28.119 --> 05:28.995
Sierra,
are you ready?

05:29.079 --> 05:32.415
<i>♪</i> I had flashes ♪

05:34.960 --> 05:37.170
<i>♪ But you saw the plan ♪</i>

05:37.254 --> 05:38.421
<i>♪ I wandered ♪</i>

05:38.505 --> 05:39.589
<i>‐♪</i> Out in the world ♪
‐Okay.

05:39.673 --> 05:43.051
<i>‐♪</i> For years ♪
‐Martin, Trevor, Stacey, go!

05:43.134 --> 05:47.889
<i>♪ While you just stayed</i>
<i>in your room ♪</i>

05:47.973 --> 05:49.933
<i>♪ I saw the crescent ♪</i>

05:50.016 --> 05:51.560
[chuckles]

05:53.478 --> 05:54.896
<i>‐♪ You saw the whole ♪</i>
‐[chuckles]

05:54.980 --> 05:56.398
<i>‐♪</i> Of the moon ♪
‐And everyone!

05:56.481 --> 05:58.650
<i>♪♪♪</i>

05:58.733 --> 06:00.610
<i>♪ The whole of the moon ♪</i>

06:02.529 --> 06:06.575
<i>♪</i> Mmm, you were there
<i>in the turnstiles ♪</i>

06:06.658 --> 06:08.577
<i>♪</i> With the wind at your heels ♪

06:08.660 --> 06:10.745
<i>♪ You stretched for the stars ♪</i>

06:10.829 --> 06:15.709
<i>♪</i> And you know how it feels
<i>to reach too high ♪</i>

06:15.792 --> 06:17.961
<i>♪ Too far ♪</i>

06:18.044 --> 06:20.922
<i>♪ Too soon ♪</i>

06:21.006 --> 06:24.634
<i>♪ You saw</i>
<i>the whole of the moon ♪</i>

06:29.514 --> 06:32.517
‐[feedback]
‐[blows]

06:32.601 --> 06:34.311
[chatter in distance]

06:34.394 --> 06:36.938
[keys clacking]

06:38.440 --> 06:42.068
Hey, Trev.
Can I borrow you for a second?

06:42.152 --> 06:43.361
Can't.

06:44.279 --> 06:45.780
I need your help.

06:45.864 --> 06:48.241
I'm writing my toast.

06:48.325 --> 06:50.160
Trevor, I know you hate me,
but consider this

06:50.243 --> 06:53.204
a favor to your sister.

06:54.122 --> 06:55.957
I don't hate you.

06:56.041 --> 06:57.542
It's okay if you do.

06:57.626 --> 06:59.127
I hated my dad, too.

06:59.210 --> 07:01.880
No. No, really, I don't.

07:01.963 --> 07:03.673
[sighs]
I just...

07:03.757 --> 07:07.385
[chuckles softly]
I wish you'd been around more.

07:12.807 --> 07:15.393
Me, too.

07:16.394 --> 07:17.604
Yeah.

07:17.687 --> 07:18.813
Good talk.

07:24.736 --> 07:26.529
Hey, how's it going?

07:26.946 --> 07:29.783
Perfect.

07:30.784 --> 07:33.078
I can't believe
they're making me do this.

07:33.620 --> 07:35.622
Well, you said yes.

07:35.705 --> 07:37.332
What was I supposed
to say?

07:37.415 --> 07:39.584
What the hell do I know
about getting married?

07:39.668 --> 07:42.170
Well, doesn't she have
some poems or something

07:42.253 --> 07:45.006
she wants people
to read?

07:45.090 --> 07:46.925
Yeah.

07:47.008 --> 07:50.136
So, then they...
say their vows,

07:50.220 --> 07:52.013
exchange rings
and then kiss, right?

07:52.097 --> 07:52.722
How hard could it be?

07:52.806 --> 07:54.099
She wants me to say something.

07:54.182 --> 07:57.894
Something important.

07:57.977 --> 07:59.688
Well,

07:59.771 --> 08:01.398
you like Colin, right?

08:01.481 --> 08:03.066
I mean, of all the boyfriends
she's ever had,

08:03.149 --> 08:04.192
he's definitely my favorite.

08:04.275 --> 08:06.027
What do you like about him?

08:06.111 --> 08:09.114
He's not a dick.

08:10.073 --> 08:11.032
He treats her well.

08:11.116 --> 08:14.411
He's a decent guy.

08:14.494 --> 08:16.788
I mean, honestly, like,
it could have been much worse.

08:16.871 --> 08:18.415
Well, why don't
you just say that?

08:18.498 --> 08:20.125
I mean, not the part
about it being worse, but...

08:20.208 --> 08:22.419
Sure, I mean, she's getting
a good deal out of it.

08:22.502 --> 08:24.546
I'm just not sure
what's in it for him.

08:24.629 --> 08:26.131
What do you mean?

08:28.466 --> 08:31.553
I just don't know why anyone
would want to marry my sister.

08:31.636 --> 08:32.053
‐Martin.
‐Dad, come on.

08:32.137 --> 08:33.972
She's a lot.

08:34.055 --> 08:36.057
Whitney is a lot.

08:36.141 --> 08:37.308
Yeah, that's what
makes her great.

08:37.392 --> 08:40.854
When I get married, I'm gonna
choose someone much easier.

08:42.689 --> 08:44.649
Yeah, well, you're welcome
to choose whoever you want,

08:44.733 --> 08:46.860
but you may change your mind
in a few years.

08:48.445 --> 08:51.072
Your sister's really smart

08:51.156 --> 08:52.323
and passionate

08:52.407 --> 08:54.617
and believes deeply in things.

08:54.701 --> 08:56.786
And, yeah, she can be
a little dramatic,

08:56.870 --> 09:00.790
but she's gonna keep his life
really interesting.

09:00.874 --> 09:02.876
I get, from where
you're sitting, it...

09:02.959 --> 09:04.627
you know, she seems
like a lot of work, but...

09:04.711 --> 09:07.380
I think you realize,
as you get older,

09:07.464 --> 09:09.632
the person you want to live
with is not, is not the one

09:09.716 --> 09:11.509
who's... keeps telling you
how wonderful you are.

09:11.593 --> 09:14.471
It's the one who you
just can't stop talking to

09:14.554 --> 09:16.723
'cause you have no idea
what she's gonna say next.

09:19.726 --> 09:23.772
I think Colin got pretty lucky,
too, you know.

09:23.855 --> 09:25.065
You should say that.

09:25.148 --> 09:27.942
[sniffs]

09:28.026 --> 09:29.903
[sighs]

09:31.029 --> 09:32.447
[chuckles]
I got to go.

09:32.530 --> 09:33.239
I'm really, really busy.

09:33.323 --> 09:35.033
Yeah, well,
good luck.

09:35.116 --> 09:36.993
You, too.

09:39.162 --> 09:41.081
[knocking]

09:41.164 --> 09:44.375
Colin?

09:46.586 --> 09:50.090
‐Hey.
‐Hey.

09:50.173 --> 09:52.467
Uh, I was just checking
to see if you're okay.

09:52.550 --> 09:54.135
D‐Do you need anything or...?

09:55.553 --> 09:58.264
They just told me
to get dressed in here, so...

09:58.348 --> 10:00.850
Of course. Yeah, no,
this is the son‐in‐law suite.

10:00.934 --> 10:04.145
I actually remember
shaving in that bathroom

10:04.229 --> 10:05.438
just before my wedding.

10:05.522 --> 10:06.773
Really?

10:08.650 --> 10:10.819
Wow, you use a straight razor.

10:10.902 --> 10:12.821
Yeah.

10:12.904 --> 10:14.030
It was my dad's.

10:14.114 --> 10:15.573
Oh, where are your parents?

10:15.657 --> 10:16.241
Are they, are they here yet?

10:16.324 --> 10:19.786
Uh, no.
[sighs]

10:19.869 --> 10:21.371
They couldn't make it, actually.

10:21.454 --> 10:23.331
Oh. Why?

10:23.414 --> 10:25.500
Well, they wanted to, of course.

10:25.583 --> 10:27.252
Got them a flight from Belfast
and everything.

10:27.335 --> 10:28.336
But, um...

10:28.419 --> 10:31.172
my dad got arrested, so...

10:31.256 --> 10:33.675
What?

10:33.758 --> 10:36.094
[inhales deeply] Yeah, I don't
know why I just told you that.

10:36.177 --> 10:38.304
Please don't tell Whitney.
I just told her he was sick.

10:38.388 --> 10:40.515
No, no. Of course I won't.

10:40.598 --> 10:43.184
I mean, is‐is everything okay?

10:43.268 --> 10:44.561
Um, anything I can do?

10:50.108 --> 10:52.652
[exhales]

10:52.735 --> 10:55.613
‐I'm sorry.
‐Colin.

10:57.782 --> 10:59.868
I shouldn't
have gotten him a ticket.

10:59.951 --> 11:01.828
I knew
he would do this.

11:01.911 --> 11:05.039
Such a waste
of fucking money.

11:05.123 --> 11:07.375
What happened?
Is he okay?

11:07.458 --> 11:09.419
He is fine.
He's just drunk.

11:09.502 --> 11:10.753
He does this.

11:10.837 --> 11:11.504
Especially when
he gets stressed.

11:11.588 --> 11:14.591
And flying stresses him out.

11:14.674 --> 11:16.467
So I should have known.

11:16.551 --> 11:19.095
Colin,

11:19.179 --> 11:21.764
I'm so sorry.

11:21.848 --> 11:24.517
How about your mother?
Is she... can she make it?

11:26.352 --> 11:28.688
I don't think so.
She...

11:28.771 --> 11:29.272
[sniffles]

11:29.355 --> 11:31.774
...missed her flight,

11:31.858 --> 11:32.984
and it's too complicated

11:33.067 --> 11:36.237
for her to figure out how to get
the ticket reissued, so...

11:38.156 --> 11:39.324
It's fine.

11:39.407 --> 11:41.117
I'll just send her
some pictures.

11:41.201 --> 11:42.202
‐She'll like that.
‐Wait.

11:42.285 --> 11:43.578
Where is she now?

11:43.661 --> 11:45.246
[exhales]
What do you mean?

11:45.330 --> 11:46.789
Well, if I get her
a new ticket,

11:46.873 --> 11:48.416
is she, is she near an airport?

11:48.499 --> 11:50.251
I mean, how‐how‐how long
is the flight?

11:50.335 --> 11:52.212
It's about seven hours.

11:52.295 --> 11:54.422
Okay, so... what,
she can be here by 10 or 11?

11:54.505 --> 11:56.591
You want to try it?

11:56.674 --> 11:58.676
You really don't have
to do that, Mr. Solloway.

11:58.760 --> 12:00.595
Look, first of all,
call me Noah.

12:00.678 --> 12:03.139
And, secondly, I'd really,
really like to help.

12:04.182 --> 12:05.725
Why?

12:06.643 --> 12:09.020
Because you're family.

12:09.103 --> 12:11.981
You get a pretty bad rap
in this family, Noah.

12:14.192 --> 12:17.278
Yeah, well, I've done
some things to deserve that.

12:17.362 --> 12:19.405
Also, the Solloway women
are pretty tough.

12:19.489 --> 12:21.741
Good luck with yours.

12:21.824 --> 12:23.660
‐[laughs]
‐[chuckles]

12:23.743 --> 12:26.537
Here's the thing about the
family you're marrying into.

12:26.621 --> 12:28.623
We're all
batshit crazy

12:28.706 --> 12:30.458
and we can be brutal
with each other.

12:30.541 --> 12:32.794
But when the shit hits the fan,

12:32.877 --> 12:34.295
we show up.

12:38.216 --> 12:38.633
It's not much, but...

12:38.716 --> 12:39.968
it's not nothing.

12:42.178 --> 12:44.806
Where I come from, it's a lot.

12:44.889 --> 12:47.141
Thank you.

12:49.227 --> 12:51.104
[chatter in distance]

12:52.230 --> 12:55.149
Yeah. Okay.

12:55.233 --> 12:56.818
So, boarding in... 90 minutes?

12:56.901 --> 13:00.488
Great. Okay, can you send me
the confirmation?

13:00.571 --> 13:02.490
Yeah, that's my e‐mail.
Thank you.

13:02.573 --> 13:04.951
Perfect. Bye.

13:06.077 --> 13:08.162
What was that about?

13:08.246 --> 13:09.205
Nothing. Wow.

13:09.289 --> 13:11.416
You look great.

13:11.499 --> 13:13.376
Thank you.

13:17.005 --> 13:19.716
This is really nice.

13:19.799 --> 13:22.135
Really, really nice.

13:31.519 --> 13:33.896
I think it's time.

13:33.980 --> 13:36.316
I know.

13:38.985 --> 13:40.903
[soft clanging, clinking]

13:40.987 --> 13:43.197
<i>♪ slow, somber music ♪</i>

13:43.281 --> 13:44.949
<i>♪♪♪</i>

13:58.296 --> 14:00.673
[birds chirping]

14:05.303 --> 14:06.596
What the...?

14:10.975 --> 14:12.060
Hey!

14:14.020 --> 14:15.188
Hey.

14:15.271 --> 14:18.274
Are you, uh, Helen Butler?

14:19.317 --> 14:19.901
No.

14:19.984 --> 14:22.570
Uh, these are
for Helen.

14:22.653 --> 14:23.362
Can you sign?

14:23.446 --> 14:25.406
Sure.

14:28.367 --> 14:29.035
Here's the note.

14:29.118 --> 14:31.204
‐Here you go.
‐All right.

14:31.287 --> 14:33.915
‐Thanks.
‐Have a good day.

14:40.922 --> 14:42.715
[van departing]

14:44.801 --> 14:47.762
It was Victor Hugo, you asshole.

14:47.845 --> 14:49.514
[horn honking]

14:49.597 --> 14:50.890
[delivery man]
Hey, buddy!

14:50.973 --> 14:53.101
Can you move out
of the way?

14:53.184 --> 14:54.685
Oh, fuck.

14:56.312 --> 14:58.648
Hey, Bruce.
Bruce.

14:58.731 --> 15:01.275
Bruce,
where are you going?

15:01.359 --> 15:02.318
It isn't safe.

15:02.401 --> 15:04.654
What isn't safe?

15:04.737 --> 15:06.280
They're after me.
I have to leave.

15:06.364 --> 15:07.115
‐Come on, let's go back‐‐
‐Don't touch me,

15:07.198 --> 15:09.283
‐you fucking pig.
‐It's okay. Okay.

15:09.367 --> 15:10.701
It's okay, Bruce.
It's fine. You're safe.

15:10.785 --> 15:13.454
Come on, let's go back inside.

15:13.538 --> 15:15.081
Don't you understand?

15:15.164 --> 15:17.125
I can't go back in there.
I don't know them.

15:17.208 --> 15:18.626
I don't know any
of those people.

15:18.709 --> 15:19.710
Well, you‐you know me.

15:19.794 --> 15:22.296
Don't you?
You know me.

15:23.381 --> 15:25.967
Michael?

15:26.050 --> 15:28.136
Michael, is that you?

15:28.219 --> 15:30.263
Yeah, it's me.

15:30.346 --> 15:31.472
How are you, Bruce?

15:31.556 --> 15:32.890
Uh, it's good
to see you again.

15:32.974 --> 15:34.892
[gasps] Oh, you made it.

15:34.976 --> 15:36.144
You made it.

15:36.227 --> 15:37.145
Yeah, I made it.

15:37.228 --> 15:39.230
Oh. They said you were dead.

15:39.313 --> 15:41.732
They told me
you weren't coming back.

15:41.816 --> 15:42.316
Well, they were wrong.

15:42.400 --> 15:44.944
[exhales]

15:45.027 --> 15:46.487
Do Mom and Dad know?

15:46.571 --> 15:47.488
No. Not‐not yet.

15:47.572 --> 15:50.408
No, I was, uh...
they're waiting for us inside.

15:50.491 --> 15:51.993
I‐I thought I'd come
and find you first.

15:52.076 --> 15:53.452
Will you come back
and s‐see them with me?

15:53.536 --> 15:55.997
Oh, Michael,

15:56.080 --> 15:57.665
I can't believe
it's really you.

15:57.748 --> 16:00.626
It's really you.

16:00.710 --> 16:03.713
Oh. Oh.

16:05.298 --> 16:09.177
My... my little brother.
My boy.

16:09.260 --> 16:10.553
Come on, Bruce.
Come on.

16:10.636 --> 16:12.013
Let's‐let's go find
Mom and Dad.

16:12.096 --> 16:13.431
Come on.

16:13.514 --> 16:15.141
You're okay.

16:23.983 --> 16:25.693
Oh, fuck.
Here, Bruce.

16:25.776 --> 16:27.862
Bruce. Come here.

16:27.945 --> 16:29.238
Quick.

16:29.322 --> 16:32.074
Hide there. Okay?
Just hide there.

16:34.035 --> 16:37.705
What are we doing?
Is this a game?

16:37.788 --> 16:38.414
Yeah, it's a game.
We have to be quiet, okay?

16:38.497 --> 16:42.001
[laughs]

16:44.629 --> 16:46.547
<i>♪ gentle music ♪</i>

16:46.631 --> 16:48.758
<i>♪♪♪</i>

17:01.020 --> 17:03.064
Oh, this is
a great hiding place.

17:03.147 --> 17:04.815
Mom and Dad
will never find us.

17:10.738 --> 17:12.448
No, they won't.

17:17.536 --> 17:20.998
They'll never even know
we were here.

17:22.917 --> 17:25.002
<i>♪♪♪</i>

17:28.422 --> 17:30.258
<i>♪♪♪</i>

17:40.685 --> 17:42.770
[wind whistling]

17:45.398 --> 17:47.275
[birds squawking]

17:57.868 --> 18:00.621
<i>♪ suspenseful music ♪</i>

18:00.705 --> 18:02.790
<i>♪♪♪</i>

18:17.972 --> 18:20.891
Oh, fuck.

18:34.363 --> 18:36.198
<i>♪♪♪</i>

18:43.789 --> 18:45.916
[glass clinking]

18:50.921 --> 18:52.882
<i>♪ contemplative music ♪</i>

18:52.965 --> 18:55.092
<i>♪♪♪</i>

19:02.433 --> 19:04.101
[sniffs]

19:19.617 --> 19:21.243
[sniffs]

19:33.506 --> 19:35.383
<i>♪♪♪</i>

19:47.144 --> 19:49.188
[birds chirping]

19:53.567 --> 19:55.319
[sighs]

19:55.403 --> 19:56.320
[car system chimes]

20:23.973 --> 20:25.474
[Joanie]
Hello?

20:29.770 --> 20:31.605
Hello.

20:31.689 --> 20:34.400
Hello.

20:37.153 --> 20:39.405
One second, then.

20:42.992 --> 20:44.869
My ears.

20:44.952 --> 20:45.995
[hearing aid chirps]

20:46.078 --> 20:47.621
What can I do for you?

20:47.705 --> 20:48.622
Can I get a cup of coffee?

20:48.706 --> 20:52.376
A customer.

20:52.460 --> 20:53.502
Welcome to the end of the world.

20:55.880 --> 20:57.173
You can sit wherever you like.

20:57.256 --> 20:58.340
I'll bring it to you.

21:04.096 --> 21:06.265
<i>♪ plaintive music ♪</i>

21:20.404 --> 21:21.489
<i>♪♪♪</i>

21:35.085 --> 21:37.213
<i>♪♪♪</i>

21:44.094 --> 21:45.930
This your first time
in Montauk?

21:46.013 --> 21:48.098
No, I grew up here.

21:48.182 --> 21:48.682
Thanks.

21:48.766 --> 21:50.935
Did you now?

21:51.018 --> 21:52.394
A local.

21:52.478 --> 21:54.522
That's a rarity around here.

21:54.605 --> 21:58.526
My mom actually worked here
for a bit before I was born.

21:58.609 --> 22:00.069
Where?

22:01.487 --> 22:04.156
Here.
This restaurant.

22:08.786 --> 22:10.746
Well, I'll be damned.

22:13.374 --> 22:16.877
Um... could I just get
some eggs?

22:16.961 --> 22:20.714
Scrambled?

22:20.798 --> 22:22.675
Coming right up.

22:27.179 --> 22:27.471
Hey.

22:30.474 --> 22:31.559
Do you know where
I can get some gas?

22:31.642 --> 22:34.311
Gas?

22:34.395 --> 22:34.895
For a car.

22:34.979 --> 22:38.774
[chuckles]
Not anymore.

22:48.826 --> 22:50.661
<i>♪♪♪</i>

23:03.132 --> 23:05.718
These are so tiny.

23:09.597 --> 23:11.432
Mom, this is taking
too long, okay?

23:11.515 --> 23:12.391
‐I'm just gonna do it myself.
‐No, no, no, no, no.

23:12.474 --> 23:13.434
I'm almost done.
I'm almost done.

23:13.517 --> 23:14.727
Stop. Stop.
Hold still.

23:14.810 --> 23:17.354
[sighs]

23:18.606 --> 23:19.773
Did everyone make it?

23:19.857 --> 23:22.610
I think so.

23:22.693 --> 23:24.278
No one canceled
last minute, right?

23:24.361 --> 23:25.738
I'm worried they might.

23:25.821 --> 23:27.197
Colin's friends are such flakes.

23:27.281 --> 23:28.282
I just... I don't want there
to be any empty seats.

23:28.365 --> 23:32.453
Well, you'd have
to ask your father.

23:32.536 --> 23:33.078
‐Why?
‐Because he was keeping

23:33.162 --> 23:35.956
the guest list.

23:36.040 --> 23:37.666
Mom, I, I asked you

23:37.750 --> 23:39.168
to take care of that.
I thought you did.

23:39.251 --> 23:40.794
Yes, I know.
But he sent out the invitations

23:40.878 --> 23:42.212
and it just seemed much simpler.

23:42.296 --> 23:43.464
And, Whitney,
does it really matter?

23:43.547 --> 23:44.798
I mean, come on.

23:44.882 --> 23:45.925
It matters to me.

23:46.008 --> 23:47.009
‐Wha... [gasps]
‐[button clatters]

23:47.092 --> 23:48.135
Okay. Seriously?
You dropped it?

23:48.218 --> 23:49.345
I, no... I...

23:49.428 --> 23:50.387
What the fuck is
wrong with you?

23:50.471 --> 23:51.805
I didn't mean to,
it's just that...

23:51.889 --> 23:54.808
it's just that you
turned so quickly.

23:54.892 --> 23:56.560
Jesus, Helen,
why are you even here?

23:56.644 --> 23:58.604
Because I... thought
you might need my help.

23:58.687 --> 24:02.191
Oh, my God. Do not make this
about you right now.

24:02.274 --> 24:04.443
I do not have time
for that today.

24:06.362 --> 24:08.822
Where did you learn to be
so hard on people, Whitney?

24:10.491 --> 24:12.534
[scoffs]

24:14.119 --> 24:16.747
Why <i>am</i> I here?

24:16.830 --> 24:19.166
If I bother you
that much?

24:19.249 --> 24:20.709
Why am I here?
Why didn't you

24:20.793 --> 24:22.378
just disinvite me
like you did your dad?

24:22.461 --> 24:24.254
Optics.
Think about it.

24:24.338 --> 24:26.090
It would have looked terrible.

24:35.265 --> 24:37.643
I do not want to have
the same relationship with you

24:37.726 --> 24:39.311
as I do
with my own mother.

24:39.395 --> 24:40.854
But I don't know how
to avoid it right now.

24:40.938 --> 24:42.606
[scoffs] Well, you could try
listening to me for a change.

24:42.690 --> 24:44.191
‐That would be a fun start.
‐I do listen to you.

24:44.274 --> 24:44.900
No, you don't. You listen
for what you want to hear.

24:44.984 --> 24:46.276
And that's not the same thing.

24:46.360 --> 24:47.277
I don't... I‐I don't...

24:47.361 --> 24:50.072
understand what you mean.

24:50.155 --> 24:52.366
Okay. Right.
Ask me a question.

24:52.449 --> 24:55.244
One that you don't think that
you already know the answer to.

24:59.540 --> 25:00.666
Are you in love?

25:03.168 --> 25:05.421
I think so.

25:05.504 --> 25:07.715
You're not sure?

25:07.798 --> 25:09.591
No.

25:09.675 --> 25:11.885
Why not?

25:11.969 --> 25:15.222
I don't know,
I'm not obsessed with him.

25:15.305 --> 25:16.724
Uh... it's not like you and Dad.

25:16.807 --> 25:19.018
I... I don't think
about him all the time.

25:19.101 --> 25:20.728
I don't wonder if he's okay.

25:20.811 --> 25:23.689
Sometimes a whole day goes by
and I just forget about him.

25:23.772 --> 25:25.232
And does that worry you?

25:25.315 --> 25:28.485
No, it doesn't worry me, Mom.
I'm not like you.

25:28.569 --> 25:31.822
I don't want my marriage to be
the great adventure of my life.

25:31.905 --> 25:33.907
Is that what you think I wanted?

25:33.991 --> 25:35.117
Isn't it?

25:35.200 --> 25:37.161
Peekaboo!
It's almost time.

25:37.244 --> 25:40.122
Are you ready?

25:40.205 --> 25:41.415
What the hell
is going on in here?

25:41.498 --> 25:45.085
Whitney, for God's sake,
get your shoes on.

25:45.169 --> 25:46.378
God, your mother is so useless.

25:46.462 --> 25:47.713
I should have known,
when I sent her

25:47.796 --> 25:48.881
in here
to help you get ready,

25:48.964 --> 25:51.008
that absolutely nothing
would be accomplished.

25:51.091 --> 25:53.427
Okay, Grandma, look,
I'm ready. See?

25:53.510 --> 25:54.803
Stand over there,
so I can see.

25:57.389 --> 25:58.474
What do you think?

25:58.557 --> 26:01.435
I think she looks perfect.

26:01.518 --> 26:02.561
She certainly looks better
than you did

26:02.644 --> 26:04.021
at your wedding.
That's something.

26:04.104 --> 26:04.980
‐Grandma.
‐Is that what you're wearing?

26:05.064 --> 26:07.816
Wow, you are really
in rare form today.

26:07.900 --> 26:09.777
Helen, I've got 60 people
in the backyard,

26:09.860 --> 26:13.614
including some shifty hooligans
masquerading as musicians.

26:13.697 --> 26:15.157
It's a band.
They're Whitney's friends.

26:15.240 --> 26:16.992
It's 42 degrees outside,

26:17.076 --> 26:18.744
your father has already
wandered off twice.

26:18.827 --> 26:20.412
He's currently tied to a chair.

26:20.496 --> 26:22.456
The chef just locked
her key in the catering van

26:22.539 --> 26:24.291
and can't get
the croquembouche out,

26:24.374 --> 26:25.167
and the dog seems to be dying.

26:25.250 --> 26:27.336
You don't have a dog!

26:27.419 --> 26:28.754
I didn't say I had a dog.

26:28.837 --> 26:30.589
I said there is a dog
on the property

26:30.672 --> 26:33.634
that seems to be perilously
close to its final demise.

26:33.717 --> 26:34.676
How's that for an omen
for my granddaughter's wedding?

26:34.760 --> 26:36.720
‐Grandma, shut the fuck up!
‐Whit, it's okay.

26:36.804 --> 26:39.139
No! No, it's not okay.
She's a fucking monster.

26:39.223 --> 26:40.766
Yes, I know,
but she's our monster.

26:40.849 --> 26:42.476
Okay, so you just go outside.

26:42.559 --> 26:44.978
Take a couple of Xanax.
Have a drink.

26:45.062 --> 26:46.688
Try to have a good time.

26:46.772 --> 26:48.315
Everything is under control.

26:48.398 --> 26:50.317
Whit, you look beautiful,
but even if you didn't,

26:50.400 --> 26:51.777
you know, it doesn't
fucking matter,

26:51.860 --> 26:54.613
'cause this is really just
one incredibly expensive day

26:54.696 --> 26:57.574
that has absolutely
no influence or augury

26:57.658 --> 26:59.118
or bearing on the rest
of your life.

26:59.201 --> 27:01.620
‐Are you ready?
‐I'm ready.

27:01.703 --> 27:03.413
<i>‐[discordant music playing]</i>
‐What's that?

27:03.497 --> 27:06.208
It's, um, Whitney's "band."

27:06.291 --> 27:08.418
Oh, God, let's do this.

27:09.503 --> 27:11.588
<i>♪♪♪</i>

27:12.381 --> 27:16.260
No, you first, daughter.

27:16.343 --> 27:18.720
[sighs]

27:18.804 --> 27:19.888
Gotcha.

27:32.401 --> 27:33.652
[applause]

27:33.735 --> 27:35.696
<i>♪ quiet, atmospheric music ♪</i>

27:35.779 --> 27:36.905
<i>♪♪♪</i>

27:43.912 --> 27:45.581
My lady.

27:47.124 --> 27:48.667
Oh, Whit,
you look amazing.

27:48.750 --> 27:49.084
[Whitney]
Thank you, honey.

27:49.167 --> 27:52.504
You, too.

27:52.588 --> 27:54.131
Thank you, Stacey,
these are beautiful.

27:54.214 --> 27:57.092
I'm so happy you're all
my children. [crying]

27:59.469 --> 28:01.263
Okay. Mom, why don't you go out

28:01.346 --> 28:02.472
and tell them
we're ready to start?

28:02.556 --> 28:04.433
‐Okay.
‐Okay.

28:04.516 --> 28:06.685
[indistinct chatter nearby]

28:09.688 --> 28:12.065
All right, you two.
You're up.

28:12.149 --> 28:13.317
Get out there.

28:13.400 --> 28:16.528
See you in a bit.

28:16.612 --> 28:17.279
So handsome.

28:17.362 --> 28:18.572
So beautiful.

28:18.655 --> 28:21.783
‐Thank you.
‐Thanks, Mom.

28:21.867 --> 28:22.242
All right, you ready?

28:22.326 --> 28:25.037
[Stacey]
Yep.

28:29.124 --> 28:30.667
[sighs]

28:44.556 --> 28:47.225
Um...

28:47.309 --> 28:48.226
How do you want to do this?

28:48.310 --> 28:51.813
Should... uh, do you want
my arm or something?

29:00.697 --> 29:02.658
[sniffles]

29:08.372 --> 29:12.834
I think...
maybe... like this?

29:16.713 --> 29:17.881
Okay.

29:22.260 --> 29:23.261
[sniffles]

29:23.345 --> 29:26.431
[sighs]

29:26.515 --> 29:28.517
Wait, you got...
oh, my gosh, right here.

29:28.600 --> 29:30.602
‐[sniffles, laughs]
‐Let me see.

29:30.686 --> 29:31.895
‐Okay.
‐Okay.

29:34.272 --> 29:35.607
[exhales]

29:35.691 --> 29:37.818
‐Ready?
‐Yes.

29:37.901 --> 29:39.695
Okay.

29:49.079 --> 29:51.164
<i>[gentle music playing]</i>

29:51.248 --> 29:53.208
[guests chatting indistinctly]

29:56.420 --> 30:00.799
<i>♪ Little airplane in the sky ♪</i>

30:00.882 --> 30:04.511
<i>♪ You point up at it ♪</i>

30:04.594 --> 30:08.932
<i>♪ I watch your face</i>
<i>as you watch it go by ♪</i>

30:09.016 --> 30:12.519
<i>♪ Everything is perfect ♪</i>

30:12.602 --> 30:16.106
<i>♪ Where would I be right now ♪</i>

30:16.189 --> 30:18.567
<i>♪ If all my dreams</i>
<i>had come true? ♪</i>

30:18.650 --> 30:23.363
<i>♪ Deep down I know somehow ♪</i>

30:23.447 --> 30:27.701
<i>♪ I'd have never</i>
<i>seen your face ♪</i>

30:27.784 --> 30:31.038
<i>♪ This world would be</i>
<i>a different place ♪</i>

30:31.121 --> 30:35.375
<i>♪ Darling, there's</i>
<i>no way to know ♪</i>

30:35.459 --> 30:38.795
<i>♪ Which way</i>
<i>your heart will go ♪</i>

30:43.467 --> 30:45.552
I just want you
to be happy, Mom.

30:45.635 --> 30:49.848
<i>♪ Summer sun on a sandy slide ♪</i>

30:49.931 --> 30:53.393
<i>♪ Silver swing set shining ♪</i>

30:53.477 --> 30:57.564
<i>♪ How can life feel so alive ♪</i>

30:57.647 --> 31:01.568
<i>♪ And still feel like dying? ♪</i>

31:01.651 --> 31:03.987
<i>♪ Where would I be right now ♪</i>

31:04.071 --> 31:08.909
<i>♪ If all my dreams</i>
<i>had come true? ♪</i>

31:08.992 --> 31:13.455
<i>♪ Deep down I know</i>
<i>somehow, I'd... ♪</i>

31:13.538 --> 31:15.082
[Martin]
Testing. One, two, three.

31:15.165 --> 31:16.249
[taps microphone]

31:16.333 --> 31:18.919
Testing. One, two, three.

31:19.002 --> 31:21.379
Hey, everyone.
Welcome to my sister's wedding.

31:22.339 --> 31:23.757
Holy shit.

31:23.840 --> 31:25.759
[laughter]

31:25.842 --> 31:28.470
<i>♪ Which way</i>
<i>your heart will go ♪</i>

31:31.223 --> 31:33.100
<i>[song ends]</i>

31:33.183 --> 31:36.144
<i>♪ Get into my car now ♪</i>

31:36.228 --> 31:37.604
<i>♪ The sun is sinking down ♪</i>

31:37.687 --> 31:40.690
<i>♪ We've got about an hour ♪</i>

31:40.774 --> 31:43.110
<i>♪ Let's leave the city ♪</i>

31:43.193 --> 31:45.070
‐Sure.
‐[laughing]

31:45.153 --> 31:47.197
<i>♪ The monkey on my back's ♪</i>

31:47.280 --> 31:50.617
<i>♪ Been going apeshit now ♪</i>

31:50.700 --> 31:52.953
<i>♪ He's got his symbols out... ♪</i>

31:53.036 --> 31:55.288
‐Who has Eddie today?
‐His parents do.

31:55.372 --> 31:56.706
They live in Great Neck.

31:56.790 --> 31:58.500
Hmm. Wow.

31:58.583 --> 32:00.794
‐Really? That's convenient.
‐[Leif] Yeah. I used

32:00.877 --> 32:02.671
to do summers out here as a kid.

32:02.754 --> 32:05.549
You know that restaurant,
The Lobster Roll?

32:05.632 --> 32:07.801
I do.

32:07.884 --> 32:10.303
[Leif]
Well, um,

32:10.387 --> 32:14.641
my greatest ambition as a kid
was to be a waiter there.

32:14.724 --> 32:17.269
‐You're kidding.
‐No. During

32:17.352 --> 32:18.812
the summers, they had
all these young, tan,

32:18.895 --> 32:20.856
gorgeous waitstaff,
and I thought

32:20.939 --> 32:24.609
life couldn't get
any cooler than that.

32:24.693 --> 32:26.319
[Sierra]
Did you ever get a job there?

32:26.403 --> 32:27.404
[Leif]
No.

32:27.487 --> 32:29.990
But I think I might shoot
something there one day.

32:30.073 --> 32:31.741
You should. That
would be amazing.

32:31.825 --> 32:33.160
Yeah, it would make
a great location.

32:34.578 --> 32:36.246
