[Thea]
Tag, you're it.

49:21.208 --> 49:22.585
[Madeline]
Oh, no!

49:22.668 --> 49:25.087
‐Yay!
‐[Thea] I got you.

49:25.171 --> 49:26.589
[girls laughing]

49:27.256 --> 49:29.717
[Noah]
Can I clear this away?

49:29.800 --> 49:32.011
Yeah.

49:32.928 --> 49:34.054
Is everything all right?

49:35.681 --> 49:37.516
What?

49:37.600 --> 49:39.685
You seem a little sad.

49:39.768 --> 49:42.062
I'm always like this.

49:44.148 --> 49:45.357
Oh, that's a good book.

49:45.441 --> 49:47.401
I'm reading that myself.

49:47.485 --> 49:48.903
Yeah, it's okay.

49:48.986 --> 49:51.197
You don't like it?

49:51.280 --> 49:54.033
I'm sort of loosely connected
to the author,

49:54.116 --> 49:56.827
so I have a kind of weird
perspective on it.

49:56.911 --> 49:58.370
Really?

49:58.454 --> 50:00.581
What's that?

50:04.001 --> 50:05.961
Are you this curious
with everyone who comes in here?

50:06.045 --> 50:10.299
Well, I don't have
many customers anymore.

50:10.382 --> 50:12.510
You're my first this week.

50:15.596 --> 50:19.350
Look, I have
a big decision to make,

50:19.433 --> 50:21.727
so if you don't mind,

50:21.810 --> 50:24.230
I'd like to be alone.

50:27.483 --> 50:28.275
Well, be brave.

50:30.277 --> 50:30.819
What?

50:30.903 --> 50:34.073
Make the difficult choice.

50:34.990 --> 50:37.117
I wasn't actually asking
for your advice.

50:37.201 --> 50:39.787
Well, I'm offering it anyway.

50:41.956 --> 50:45.459
The universe rewards courage.

50:45.543 --> 50:47.586
Mister, I just found out

50:47.670 --> 50:49.338
that my mom's boyfriend
murdered her

50:49.421 --> 50:50.756
30 years ago and
got away with it,

50:50.839 --> 50:53.092
so I don't need
your fucking advice.

50:53.968 --> 50:55.678
How much do I owe you?

50:55.761 --> 50:57.596
What did you say?

50:57.680 --> 50:59.515
‐How much do I owe you?
‐No, what did...

50:59.598 --> 51:00.975
What did you say
about your mother?

51:01.058 --> 51:02.893
You know what?

51:02.977 --> 51:03.561
‐Charge me anything you want.
‐No.

51:03.644 --> 51:06.105
Wait.

51:06.188 --> 51:07.439
<i>♪ tense, dramatic music ♪</i>

51:07.523 --> 51:09.650
<i>♪♪♪</i>

51:27.418 --> 51:29.295
[door opens]

51:34.717 --> 51:37.386
‐Oh, my God. Oh, my God.
‐What the fuck?

51:37.469 --> 51:39.305
‐You have a shotgun?
‐What are you doing here?

51:39.388 --> 51:41.807
‐Where did you get a shotgun?
‐It's my father's.

51:41.890 --> 51:43.434
No shit.
That must be an antique.

51:43.517 --> 51:44.560
‐Can I see it?
‐EJ.

51:44.643 --> 51:46.854
Okay. Okay. Not the
right thing to say.

51:46.937 --> 51:47.980
How'd you find me?

51:48.063 --> 51:48.856
Sorry, were you trying to hide?

51:48.939 --> 51:49.815
I took my bracelet off.

51:49.898 --> 51:52.443
Because we had sex last night.

51:52.526 --> 51:53.652
I left it at a restaurant.

51:53.736 --> 51:54.653
And I thought
we kind of had a connection.

51:54.737 --> 51:56.989
I'm untraceable.
My own husband has no idea

51:57.072 --> 51:58.240
‐where I am right now.
‐It wasn't hard.

51:58.324 --> 52:00.492
I have a tracking device
in my car. Wait, what?

52:00.576 --> 52:02.661
‐You have a what?
‐What did you just say?

52:02.745 --> 52:05.497
[sighs]
I think you heard me.

52:05.581 --> 52:07.666
Can you put the gun down?

52:17.134 --> 52:19.678
Well, I have to admit,
I feel kind of used.

52:19.762 --> 52:22.306
‐Sorry.
‐You didn't

52:22.389 --> 52:23.849
seem like the type to lie.

52:23.932 --> 52:27.102
I'm kind of a disaster
of a person, EJ.

52:27.186 --> 52:29.688
I thought you would have
figured that out by now.

52:31.398 --> 52:33.317
How'd it go with Ben?

52:33.400 --> 52:34.777
Oh, it was terrific.

52:34.860 --> 52:37.071
I signed some kind of release
when I first got there.

52:37.154 --> 52:38.572
Didn't look at it.

52:38.656 --> 52:42.743
And apparently
I admitted to being mental.

52:42.826 --> 52:44.286
What?

52:44.370 --> 52:46.538
So when I brought
the police back,

52:46.622 --> 52:48.082
he showed them the release
and played them a recording

52:48.165 --> 52:50.417
of me saying
I wanted to kill him.

52:50.501 --> 52:52.294
‐What?
‐And they sided with him.

52:52.378 --> 52:54.797
Oh, my God, Joanie.

52:54.880 --> 52:56.507
I'm so sorry.

52:56.840 --> 52:58.717
Yeah.

52:58.801 --> 53:01.220
Guess I'll just have
to finish this myself.

53:01.303 --> 53:04.431
So, what, you're just gonna
go back and shoot him?

53:04.515 --> 53:06.433
Looks likely.

53:06.517 --> 53:08.310
They'll put you
away for life.

53:08.394 --> 53:09.937
It'll be worth it.

53:10.020 --> 53:12.272
I have a better idea.

53:12.356 --> 53:14.525
‐What?
‐Run away with me.

53:14.608 --> 53:17.611
I just told you I was married.

53:17.695 --> 53:19.405
I don't care.

53:19.488 --> 53:20.698
Why not?

53:20.781 --> 53:23.075
Because you obviously
don't care.

53:23.158 --> 53:25.285
You're clearly not happy
with your husband.

53:25.369 --> 53:26.245
If you were, you wouldn't
be here with me.

53:26.328 --> 53:30.916
I was alone here.
You just stalked me.

53:30.999 --> 53:32.918
My job is flying me
to Vienna tomorrow evening

53:33.001 --> 53:34.211
to speak at a conference.

53:34.294 --> 53:36.588
Why don't you come with me?

53:36.672 --> 53:40.008
And we can just... keep going.

53:44.263 --> 53:49.143
Sorry.
I have to finish this.

53:51.812 --> 53:52.938
What good will it do
to kill him?

53:53.021 --> 53:54.189
It's not gonna bring
your mother back.

53:54.273 --> 53:55.441
That's not what this is about.

53:55.524 --> 53:56.900
‐He can't just get away with it.
‐Joanie...

53:56.984 --> 53:58.861
Hey, hey, I like you.

53:58.944 --> 54:01.238
I really like you.

54:01.321 --> 54:02.781
You're fucking honest.

54:02.865 --> 54:04.575
You live your life
with your eyes still open.

54:04.658 --> 54:08.328
And almost nobody fucking
does that anymore.

54:08.412 --> 54:11.248
[sighs]
I'm so sick of trying

54:11.331 --> 54:13.292
to fix my parents' mistakes.

54:13.375 --> 54:16.253
We didn't fuck this planet up,
they did.

54:16.336 --> 54:18.589
Why should we have to fix it?

54:18.672 --> 54:20.883
Let them go, Joanie.

54:20.966 --> 54:22.134
Let them all go.

54:22.217 --> 54:25.012
You don't owe your life
to any of them.

54:37.357 --> 54:38.734
Okay.

54:38.817 --> 54:41.403
Wait, what? Really?

54:41.487 --> 54:42.738
That speech,
that speech worked?

54:42.821 --> 54:46.283
Car's out of gas.

54:46.366 --> 54:46.992
I figured.

54:47.075 --> 54:48.869
I brought some with me.

54:48.952 --> 54:52.372
Okay, let's go.

55:02.799 --> 55:03.800
<i>♪ contemplative music ♪</i>

55:03.884 --> 55:06.720
<i>♪♪♪</i>

55:12.643 --> 55:16.230
What?

55:18.941 --> 55:20.817
I have to tell
you something.

55:22.236 --> 55:24.029
I, um...

55:24.112 --> 55:27.366
haven't been entirely
honest with you either.

55:27.449 --> 55:29.493
Oh, God.

55:29.576 --> 55:30.953
Are you married, too?

55:31.036 --> 55:35.624
[chuckles]
No. But, um...

55:35.707 --> 55:38.210
My full name is
Eddie James Ullah.

55:38.293 --> 55:41.296
Does that mean
anything to you?

55:41.380 --> 55:42.005
‐Should it?
‐No.

55:42.089 --> 55:45.676
No, not necessarily.

55:45.759 --> 55:50.389
It's just that my father
was sort of...

55:50.472 --> 55:52.432
loosely affiliated
with your mother.

55:52.516 --> 55:55.269
What?

55:56.853 --> 56:00.065
Alison's second husband
Noah Solloway...

56:00.148 --> 56:03.569
his first wife was a woman
named Helen Solloway.

56:03.652 --> 56:07.698
And after they divorced,
she met my father.

56:07.781 --> 56:10.033
Your mother is Helen Solloway?

56:10.117 --> 56:11.702
Uh, no.

56:11.785 --> 56:13.954
Um, my mother's name is Sierra.

56:14.037 --> 56:14.955
My father's name was Vik.

56:15.038 --> 56:17.708
They had an affair
when he was with Helen,

56:17.791 --> 56:21.712
and that's where I come from.

56:21.795 --> 56:22.212
Are we related?

56:22.296 --> 56:24.298
What? No, no, no.

56:24.381 --> 56:27.301
‐Are you sure?
‐Yes. No way.

56:27.384 --> 56:29.094
My mother is your mother's

56:29.177 --> 56:32.389
ex‐husband's ex‐wife's
new partner's lover.

56:32.472 --> 56:35.225
So we could not be less related.

56:35.309 --> 56:37.352
Did you know I was gonna be
in the graveyard that day?

56:37.436 --> 56:39.313
‐How would I have known that?
‐I don't know.

56:39.396 --> 56:40.606
Why didn't you just
tell me who you were?

56:40.689 --> 56:41.732
[scoffs]

56:41.815 --> 56:43.400
Look, it's like six degrees
of separation.

56:43.483 --> 56:44.109
It's not a big deal.

56:44.192 --> 56:46.278
Well, then, why did you hide it?

56:46.361 --> 56:47.362
Well, I wasn't trying
to hide it.

56:47.446 --> 56:48.447
Just stop the car.

56:48.530 --> 56:49.906
‐Come on.
‐Please stop the car.

56:57.789 --> 56:59.666
Joanie, you're overreacting.

56:59.750 --> 57:00.792
Nothing has changed.

57:00.876 --> 57:02.252
I'm still the same
person I was

57:02.336 --> 57:05.005
‐30 seconds ago in that car.
‐You lied to me.

57:05.088 --> 57:08.342
I didn't lie, I just didn't
tell you the whole story.

57:08.425 --> 57:09.468
And you didn't tell me
the whole story.

57:09.551 --> 57:10.052
You've been married
this whole time.

57:10.135 --> 57:12.638
I mean, come on.

57:12.721 --> 57:14.139
[chuckles]

57:14.222 --> 57:15.057
I thought we understood
each other.

57:15.140 --> 57:17.476
What is it you thought
you understood?

57:17.559 --> 57:19.394
That we're not sheep.

57:19.478 --> 57:21.605
That we both play
by different rules.

57:24.358 --> 57:25.192
This is stupid.

57:25.275 --> 57:28.528
‐I can't go to Vienna with you.
‐Why not?

57:28.612 --> 57:30.489
We were just fucking, EJ,
that's all it was.

57:30.572 --> 57:32.783
Why are you trying to turn it
into something else?

57:32.866 --> 57:35.744
Are you really so desperate
for someone to love?

57:38.413 --> 57:39.539
I guess I am.

57:41.917 --> 57:42.834
What are you even doing here?

57:42.918 --> 57:45.337
Why are you so obsessed
with my family?

57:45.420 --> 57:47.297
Is it some sort of
transitive whore property?

57:47.381 --> 57:48.674
What?!

57:48.757 --> 57:49.966
Your mother and my mother

57:50.050 --> 57:51.551
both fucked over the same woman.

57:51.635 --> 57:52.928
My mother and Helen
were friends.

57:53.011 --> 57:54.137
Right.

57:54.221 --> 57:55.555
Helen was like a
second mother to me.

57:55.639 --> 57:57.766
There‐there is such a
thing as forgiveness.

57:57.849 --> 58:01.269
I realize that that's completely
out of your frame of reference,

58:01.353 --> 58:04.106
but there are certain people
who are actually capable of it.

58:04.189 --> 58:05.649
And believe it or not,
this place was part

58:05.732 --> 58:07.192
of my childhood, too.

58:07.275 --> 58:09.194
My mother and I
came out here

58:09.277 --> 58:11.029
and stayed with Helen's
parents when I was young.

58:11.113 --> 58:13.365
I worked construction here
when I was in college.

58:13.448 --> 58:14.950
I even helped restore
the Lobster Roll

58:15.033 --> 58:15.784
when Noah bought
it, so you're not

58:15.867 --> 58:16.702
‐the only person...
‐Wait, what?

58:16.785 --> 58:18.412
...who this town
means something to.

58:18.495 --> 58:20.872
And, yeah, yeah, I don't know.

58:20.956 --> 58:22.666
Maybe I was attracted to you

58:22.749 --> 58:25.961
because we shared
a certain history.

58:26.044 --> 58:26.962
Because I thought
you might be able

58:27.045 --> 58:28.714
to understand my pain,
and I might be able

58:28.797 --> 58:29.881
to understand yours.

58:29.965 --> 58:32.217
‐Is that such a crime?

58:32.300 --> 58:33.593
‐No.
‐And I wanted to tell you.

58:33.677 --> 58:35.554
I was going to, but...

58:35.637 --> 58:38.056
you were just always dealing
with so much trauma,

58:38.140 --> 58:40.016
you didn't really let me
get a word in edgewise.

58:40.100 --> 58:42.811
You're right.

58:51.153 --> 58:54.698
So...
[exhales]

58:55.991 --> 58:56.658
Okay.

58:58.618 --> 59:02.873
I meant everything
I said back there.

59:04.708 --> 59:08.295
So will you please get
back in the car now?

59:08.378 --> 59:10.297
‐Please.
‐EJ, this isn't right.

59:10.380 --> 59:12.382
We're just gonna wind up
hating each other.

59:12.466 --> 59:13.508
No, I won't.

59:13.592 --> 59:16.261
Yes, you will.

59:16.344 --> 59:18.263
Maybe not today,
maybe not tomorrow,

59:18.346 --> 59:19.723
but soon and for the rest
of your life.

59:21.600 --> 59:22.893
So you have seen a movie.

59:22.976 --> 59:24.686
It was my mother's
favorite film.

59:24.770 --> 59:26.521
Why am I not surprised?

59:26.605 --> 59:27.689
[sighs]

59:29.941 --> 59:31.943
<i>♪ quiet, haunting music ♪</i>

59:32.027 --> 59:33.653
<i>♪♪♪</i>

59:35.906 --> 59:38.742
So, what, you're just gonna
go back to your husband?

59:40.827 --> 59:43.205
No, I don't think so.

59:43.914 --> 59:46.708
So where the hell will you go?

59:46.792 --> 59:49.294
I don't know.

59:53.006 --> 59:56.593
Your mother and Helen
were really friends?

59:57.552 --> 59:59.179
Good friends.

1:00:00.388 --> 1:00:02.557
So it's possible.

1:00:02.641 --> 1:00:04.351
What's possible?

1:00:04.434 --> 1:00:06.770
To do things differently.

1:00:10.982 --> 1:00:14.528
Can I at least give you
a lift somewhere?

1:00:17.239 --> 1:00:20.116
I'd like to walk.

1:00:23.912 --> 1:00:25.747
<i>♪♪♪</i>

1:00:36.758 --> 1:00:37.884
[engine starts]

1:01:07.998 --> 1:01:10.458
Hello again.

1:01:11.710 --> 1:01:14.379
Hey, Noah.

1:01:17.340 --> 1:01:19.551
Your father knew.

1:01:19.634 --> 1:01:21.469
Knew what?

1:01:21.553 --> 1:01:24.180
He always said
Ben must have killed her.

1:01:24.264 --> 1:01:27.851
'Cause she would never
have chosen to leave you.

1:01:27.934 --> 1:01:29.311
My dad said that?

1:01:29.394 --> 1:01:31.271
That surprises you?

1:01:31.354 --> 1:01:34.232
Um, a little, actually.

1:01:34.316 --> 1:01:37.777
He spent his entire life
saying the opposite.

1:01:37.861 --> 1:01:39.529
Well, what did he tell you?

1:01:39.613 --> 1:01:42.449
That she was crazy.

1:01:42.532 --> 1:01:45.243
That he tried to save her
and he couldn't.

1:01:45.327 --> 1:01:47.871
And that we were
better off without her.

1:01:47.954 --> 1:01:49.789
Oh, wow.

1:01:49.873 --> 1:01:51.791
That breaks my heart.

1:01:55.211 --> 1:01:58.757
You have to understand, Joanie,
your father was

1:01:58.840 --> 1:02:01.217
carrying a tremendous
amount of pain.

1:02:01.301 --> 1:02:04.638
Sounds like you cared about him.

1:02:04.721 --> 1:02:06.890
Well, "cared" is a strong word,
I mean...

1:02:06.973 --> 1:02:09.059
[chuckles softly]

1:02:09.142 --> 1:02:11.227
No, I respected Cole.

1:02:12.354 --> 1:02:14.814
I think,
under the circumstances,

1:02:14.898 --> 1:02:16.858
that's the most
one could expect.

1:02:19.152 --> 1:02:21.780
How long have you
been back in Montauk?

1:02:21.863 --> 1:02:24.115
I moved back here after
my oldest daughter's wedding,

1:02:24.199 --> 1:02:26.534
which was 30 years ago now.

1:02:26.618 --> 1:02:29.871
‐That's when we left.
‐I know.

1:02:29.955 --> 1:02:32.457
And the day Cole
came back into town,

1:02:32.540 --> 1:02:34.167
he walked through
that door and...

1:02:34.250 --> 1:02:35.293
[chuckles]

1:02:35.377 --> 1:02:38.463
...I think both of us
nearly had a heart attack.

1:02:38.546 --> 1:02:40.924
[laughs softly]

1:02:41.007 --> 1:02:43.885
But time has a habit of making
these‐these big things

1:02:43.969 --> 1:02:46.554
seem small somehow.

1:02:46.638 --> 1:02:48.473
[chuckles]

1:02:48.556 --> 1:02:51.101
It's so good to see you, Joanie.

1:02:51.184 --> 1:02:53.645
It really is so good to see you.

1:02:53.728 --> 1:02:55.105
Tell me about your life.

1:02:55.188 --> 1:02:58.733
What‐what do you, uh,
what do you do?

1:02:58.817 --> 1:03:00.694
I'm a coastal engineer.

1:03:00.777 --> 1:03:03.196
I'm trying to save
the world from drowning.

1:03:03.279 --> 1:03:05.615
Really?

1:03:07.575 --> 1:03:08.076
Do you have any children?

1:03:08.159 --> 1:03:10.328
Two.

1:03:10.412 --> 1:03:12.872
Boys or girls?

1:03:12.956 --> 1:03:15.542
Daughters.
Thea and Madeline.

1:03:15.625 --> 1:03:18.545
That's wonderful, Joanie.

1:03:19.504 --> 1:03:20.839
But...

1:03:20.922 --> 1:03:23.883
I can only love them
when I'm away from them.

1:03:23.967 --> 1:03:26.720
When I'm away from them,
I miss them terribly.

1:03:26.803 --> 1:03:31.683
But when I'm with them,
I can't...

1:03:31.766 --> 1:03:34.060
I can't even hold them
and I don't know why.

1:03:38.648 --> 1:03:40.400
I have this friend who's a, uh,

1:03:40.483 --> 1:03:44.154
he's an epigeneticist.

1:03:44.237 --> 1:03:45.864
And he has a theory

1:03:45.947 --> 1:03:48.241
about trauma being passed down.

1:03:48.324 --> 1:03:50.535
What's his name?

1:03:50.618 --> 1:03:52.328
Uh, Eddie. He's like a,

1:03:52.412 --> 1:03:54.247
he's kind of like
a‐a nephew of mine.

1:03:54.330 --> 1:03:56.750
Fascinating.

1:03:56.833 --> 1:03:57.959
‐Go on.
‐Well, he says that trauma

1:03:58.043 --> 1:04:02.756
can be passed from one
generation to another.

1:04:02.839 --> 1:04:04.966
That it actually changes
the DNA.

1:04:05.050 --> 1:04:08.845
And he says there
are studies where, uh,

1:04:08.928 --> 1:04:13.224
where there are rats who...

1:04:14.517 --> 1:04:16.269
...who are shocked

1:04:16.352 --> 1:04:20.815
every time they, uh,
smell cherry blossom.

1:04:20.899 --> 1:04:22.817
And then they breed the rats

1:04:22.901 --> 1:04:27.572
and their babies are afraid
of cherry blossom.

1:04:27.655 --> 1:04:28.782
Wow. Amazing.

1:04:28.865 --> 1:04:31.284
Anyway, my point is
that your parents

1:04:31.367 --> 1:04:32.077
went through
a lot of trauma.

1:04:32.160 --> 1:04:35.663
They, I mean,
they lost a child.

1:04:35.747 --> 1:04:37.248
So it would make sense
that you, too,

1:04:37.332 --> 1:04:39.209
were afraid of loss.

1:04:40.668 --> 1:04:43.755
And maybe even a bit
paralyzed by it.

1:04:43.838 --> 1:04:45.757
Yeah, no, I know a bit
about that theory.

1:04:45.840 --> 1:04:47.300
There's a question
about whether the children

1:04:47.383 --> 1:04:50.261
of trauma survivors
also inherit their resilience.

1:04:50.345 --> 1:04:52.889
Oh, I didn't know that.

1:04:52.972 --> 1:04:54.766
That's wonderful.

1:04:54.849 --> 1:04:56.726
So maybe you inherited
her resilience

1:04:56.810 --> 1:04:57.644
as well.

1:04:57.727 --> 1:04:59.979
You mean his resilience.

1:05:00.063 --> 1:05:02.190
No, no, no, I mean hers.

1:05:02.273 --> 1:05:05.610
No. No offense to Cole,
but he‐he never changed.

1:05:05.693 --> 1:05:07.028
I mean, your mother always said

1:05:07.112 --> 1:05:10.115
that Cole used to run away
from his problems.

1:05:10.198 --> 1:05:11.908
But Alison, she was
always working on herself.

1:05:11.991 --> 1:05:14.452
She was a work in progress
and she knew it.

1:05:14.536 --> 1:05:17.789
She was so present.

1:05:17.872 --> 1:05:22.627
Feeling everything
so deeply and...

1:05:22.710 --> 1:05:25.505
She made herself stay awake
and was so disappointed

1:05:25.588 --> 1:05:28.550
when other people seem

1:05:28.633 --> 1:05:32.262
so asleep in their lives.

1:05:32.345 --> 1:05:35.723
Noah, when I was four years old,

1:05:35.807 --> 1:05:39.352
she dumped me on Cole and
Luisa's doorstep and took off.

1:05:39.435 --> 1:05:41.271
To get help.

1:05:41.354 --> 1:05:43.314
And then, six months later,
she came back

1:05:43.398 --> 1:05:45.191
and she fought
your father in court.

1:05:45.275 --> 1:05:45.817
No, she didn't.

1:05:45.900 --> 1:05:48.319
You‐you don't know this?

1:05:48.403 --> 1:05:51.489
I thought they just
let her have me back

1:05:51.573 --> 1:05:53.575
because they felt sorry for her.

1:05:53.658 --> 1:05:55.243
No, Joanie, no, no.

1:05:55.326 --> 1:05:57.662
Cole and Luisa tried
to keep you from her.

1:05:57.745 --> 1:06:00.540
She had
to humiliate herself.

1:06:00.623 --> 1:06:03.543
It was devastating.
You... they never told you this?

1:06:04.627 --> 1:06:06.754
Oh, Jesus Christ.

1:06:08.756 --> 1:06:10.675
Joanie, it's very important
you know this:

1:06:10.758 --> 1:06:13.928
you were her whole life.

1:06:14.012 --> 1:06:17.223
Everything she did,
she did for you.

1:06:17.307 --> 1:06:22.437
She tried to get help so that
she could be there for you.

1:06:22.520 --> 1:06:26.024
She was trying to give you
a better life than she had,

1:06:26.107 --> 1:06:28.776
and she was succeeding.

1:06:30.945 --> 1:06:35.325
You know, she's...
she's one of the only people

1:06:35.408 --> 1:06:36.826
I've ever met in my whole life

1:06:36.910 --> 1:06:40.121
who, who actually
managed to change.

1:06:40.205 --> 1:06:44.334
When I met her, she was
this shell of a person,

1:06:44.417 --> 1:06:46.711
and by the time she died,
she had a job

1:06:46.794 --> 1:06:49.672
helping other people

1:06:49.756 --> 1:06:54.260
heal from the same trauma
that she had and...

1:06:54.344 --> 1:06:57.013
Do you know
how difficult that is?

1:06:58.306 --> 1:07:00.600
How few people actually
achieve that?

1:07:00.683 --> 1:07:03.436
She was still dating
married men.

1:07:04.312 --> 1:07:06.564
Oh, she didn't know
he was married.

1:07:06.648 --> 1:07:07.774
What‐what happened
with Ben, that...

1:07:07.857 --> 1:07:11.110
that was not her fault.

1:07:12.445 --> 1:07:14.739
Well, what good did it do her?

1:07:16.032 --> 1:07:18.159
All those changes?

1:07:20.995 --> 1:07:23.665
‐He killed her anyway.
‐Joanie,

1:07:23.748 --> 1:07:26.376
if the lesson you're taking away

1:07:26.459 --> 1:07:28.086
from your mother's death
is not to try,

1:07:28.169 --> 1:07:30.630
then that's a great,
great tragedy.

1:07:30.713 --> 1:07:33.383
Change is hard.

1:07:34.008 --> 1:07:36.386
It takes a long time.

1:07:36.469 --> 1:07:39.055
Sometimes m‐more
than a lifetime.

1:07:39.138 --> 1:07:41.474
What the fuck does that mean?

1:07:41.557 --> 1:07:43.935
<i>♪ slow, somber music</i> ♪

1:07:44.018 --> 1:07:48.773
Sometimes we can
only start journeys

1:07:48.856 --> 1:07:52.402
that our children
have to finish for us.

1:07:54.362 --> 1:07:56.322
It's too late
to hear those things.

1:07:56.406 --> 1:07:58.658
‐It's not too late.
‐Yes, it is.

1:07:58.741 --> 1:08:00.952
I've already
screwed it all up.

1:08:01.035 --> 1:08:03.579
I can't go off
with someone new.

1:08:03.663 --> 1:08:05.999
And I can't go home.

1:08:06.082 --> 1:08:09.544
So, instead,
I'm fucking stuck here

1:08:09.627 --> 1:08:13.256
in some sort of
seafood purgatory...

1:08:15.717 --> 1:08:17.427
...talking to you.

1:08:17.510 --> 1:08:20.471
[laughs softly]
Why can't you go home?

1:08:22.432 --> 1:08:25.768
Why don't you tell me, Noah?
You seem to know a lot.

1:08:25.852 --> 1:08:30.064
Why... why can't I go home?

1:08:30.982 --> 1:08:34.485
Well, maybe 'cause it's hard.

1:08:34.569 --> 1:08:36.529
Going home is hard.

1:08:37.113 --> 1:08:40.700
Staying with someone,

1:08:40.783 --> 1:08:43.786
loving them no matter what,

1:08:43.870 --> 1:08:46.456
that's hard.

1:08:46.539 --> 1:08:48.666
It's so easy to...

1:08:48.750 --> 1:08:53.004
go find someone new,

1:08:53.087 --> 1:08:55.006
reinvent yourself in their eyes,

1:08:55.089 --> 1:08:57.425
and try once more
to live without flaw,

1:08:57.508 --> 1:08:59.052
but sooner or later
you realize

1:08:59.135 --> 1:09:00.511
the only thing
you're running from is death.

1:09:00.595 --> 1:09:02.180
[chuckles]

1:09:02.263 --> 1:09:05.725
It's not another person
at all, it's...

1:09:05.808 --> 1:09:09.437
it's death, and...

1:09:09.520 --> 1:09:12.482
when that finally occurs
to you, you...

1:09:14.609 --> 1:09:15.360
...you yearn more than anything

1:09:15.443 --> 1:09:18.321
for someone
who really knows you.

1:09:20.531 --> 1:09:23.868
Who really knows
every inch of you.

1:09:24.827 --> 1:09:27.955
And will remember you
when you're gone.

1:09:31.751 --> 1:09:33.669
What are you trying to say?

1:09:33.753 --> 1:09:35.338
What I'm trying
to say is that

1:09:35.421 --> 1:09:37.382
if...

1:09:37.465 --> 1:09:41.594
if trauma and pain
can echo through generations,

1:09:41.677 --> 1:09:44.097
then so can love.

1:09:46.307 --> 1:09:50.895
If abandonment
can ripple across time,

1:09:50.978 --> 1:09:54.565
then so can presence.

1:09:56.150 --> 1:09:58.569
I mean, you‐you've suffered
a lot of loss in your life,

1:09:58.653 --> 1:10:00.238
Joanie, but you've also had

1:10:00.321 --> 1:10:01.406
a lot of love.

1:10:04.742 --> 1:10:09.288
And you may not be able
to save the Earth.

1:10:11.332 --> 1:10:14.001
But you can be there
for your children.

1:10:14.085 --> 1:10:17.255
No matter what happens.

1:10:34.522 --> 1:10:37.817
<i>♪ Same clothes the last time ♪</i>

1:10:37.900 --> 1:10:39.527
<i>♪ You disappointed me ♪</i>

1:10:39.610 --> 1:10:44.031
<i>♪ I've got those same clothes</i>
<i>the last time ♪</i>

1:10:44.115 --> 1:10:48.578
<i>♪ You disappointed me ♪</i>

1:10:48.661 --> 1:10:50.079
<i>♪ You gotta help me... ♪</i>

1:10:50.163 --> 1:10:53.708
Don't tell anyone,
but I miss Dad.

1:10:53.791 --> 1:10:55.168
Yeah.

1:10:57.712 --> 1:10:58.755
Where do you think
he is tonight?

1:10:58.838 --> 1:11:01.966
He's here.

1:11:02.049 --> 1:11:03.468
What do you mean? He's here?

1:11:03.551 --> 1:11:04.927
No, no. He's in Montauk.

1:11:05.011 --> 1:11:06.387
I think.

1:11:06.471 --> 1:11:07.305
At least he was this morning.

1:11:07.388 --> 1:11:10.308
‐Why?
‐We rehearsed your flash mob.

1:11:10.391 --> 1:11:12.560
Martin.

1:11:12.643 --> 1:11:15.563
I don't think you were
supposed to know that.

1:11:15.646 --> 1:11:16.689
‐[indistinct chatter]
<i>‐[dance music playing]</i>

1:11:16.773 --> 1:11:19.525
<i>♪♪♪</i>

1:11:24.238 --> 1:11:25.948
How could you not tell me
he was in Montauk?

1:11:26.032 --> 1:11:28.117
He told us not to.

1:11:28.201 --> 1:11:30.411
He thought it
would upset you.

1:11:30.495 --> 1:11:32.330
[Stacey]
But he had to be here.

1:11:32.413 --> 1:11:33.414
He basically planned
the entire wedding.

1:11:33.498 --> 1:11:35.625
I thought Mom took over
the wedding planning.

1:11:35.708 --> 1:11:37.168
She told me she would.

1:11:37.251 --> 1:11:41.672
No, I think maybe you told her
that she was going to.

1:11:41.756 --> 1:11:42.256
[Martin]
Look, it was a group effort,

1:11:42.340 --> 1:11:43.216
and we all pitched in.

1:11:43.299 --> 1:11:45.510
Yeah. I don't know
why you're so upset.

1:11:45.593 --> 1:11:47.261
I think it came
together really well.

1:11:47.345 --> 1:11:48.262
What, so he's just somewhere
by himself right now

1:11:48.346 --> 1:11:50.765
while we're all
enjoying the party?

1:11:50.848 --> 1:11:52.183
Well, you said
you didn't want him here.

1:11:52.266 --> 1:11:54.310
Where the fuck is
he even staying?

1:11:54.393 --> 1:11:55.853
At the Memory Motel.

1:11:55.937 --> 1:11:56.771
Of course
you know that, Stacey.

1:11:56.854 --> 1:11:58.523
You're such a fucking
daddy's girl.

1:11:58.606 --> 1:11:59.398
Hey. She's 12.

1:11:59.482 --> 1:12:02.360
Look, I just think
it's really awful

1:12:02.443 --> 1:12:04.612
that none of you told me
that he was coming here.

1:12:04.695 --> 1:12:07.031
As if I'm the
crazy one, like...

1:12:07.114 --> 1:12:08.199
We don't think
you're crazy, Whit.

1:12:08.282 --> 1:12:10.159
We just wanted you
to have a good day.

1:12:10.243 --> 1:12:12.286
All of us,
him included.

1:12:12.370 --> 1:12:13.871
How could you let him come here?

1:12:13.955 --> 1:12:16.374
I thought you understood.
You of all people.

1:12:16.457 --> 1:12:18.084
I do understand.

1:12:18.167 --> 1:12:19.794
Your father's made
some real mistakes

1:12:19.877 --> 1:12:21.838
and you've had to bear
the brunt of them.

1:12:21.921 --> 1:12:23.214
But he does
love you, Whit.

1:12:23.297 --> 1:12:25.216
And he wanted
to do this for you.

1:12:25.299 --> 1:12:27.718
Even if he couldn't
be here to see it.

1:12:27.802 --> 1:12:29.637
<i>♪♪♪</i>

1:12:37.311 --> 1:12:40.439
[sniffles]
Yeah. He's got you all fooled.

1:12:41.732 --> 1:12:44.277
He bought my mother
a plane ticket.

1:12:44.360 --> 1:12:45.570
He didn't have to do that.

1:12:48.322 --> 1:12:49.699
He did?

1:12:54.203 --> 1:12:55.288
Fuck.

1:12:55.371 --> 1:12:57.248
[Bruce]
Excuse me.

1:12:57.331 --> 1:12:58.583
Could I get a dance
with the bride?

1:13:00.626 --> 1:13:02.128
Of course, Grandpa.

1:13:06.883 --> 1:13:07.884
<i>[slow piano music playing]</i>

1:13:07.967 --> 1:13:10.803
<i>♪♪♪</i>

1:13:25.735 --> 1:13:28.613
‐What's wrong, kiddo?
‐[laughs softly]

1:13:28.696 --> 1:13:31.574
You're awfully perceptive
for someone with dementia.

1:13:31.657 --> 1:13:34.577
[chuckles]
Well, this is a good day.

1:13:36.871 --> 1:13:38.581
So tell me,
what's on your mind?

1:13:38.664 --> 1:13:42.752
It's your wedding day.
You don't look happy.

1:13:42.835 --> 1:13:43.878
Sometimes I don't know
what to think.

1:13:43.961 --> 1:13:45.630
About what?

1:13:45.713 --> 1:13:50.176
If people hurt you very badly,
do you have to forgive them?

1:13:51.135 --> 1:13:53.679
No.

1:13:53.763 --> 1:13:55.848
But sometimes it hurts you
more than it hurts them

1:13:55.932 --> 1:13:57.600
to hold a grudge.

1:13:59.518 --> 1:14:02.521
What's it all for, then?

1:14:02.605 --> 1:14:04.690
If people can act however
they want and get forgiven,

1:14:04.774 --> 1:14:05.983
then what is the point
of trying to be good

1:14:06.067 --> 1:14:08.235
in the first place?

1:14:10.154 --> 1:14:13.407
I think it's about what kind
of life you want to live.

1:14:13.491 --> 1:14:16.661
You will have plenty
of opportunities

1:14:16.744 --> 1:14:19.163
to be angry in your life.

1:14:19.246 --> 1:14:21.999
You have less chance
to love people, though.

1:14:22.083 --> 1:14:24.001
Really love them.

1:14:24.085 --> 1:14:25.461
So you just...

1:14:26.963 --> 1:14:28.839
...you want to be careful
how many of those opportunities

1:14:28.923 --> 1:14:30.341
you squander.

1:14:30.424 --> 1:14:34.220
I think young people believe
they'll just keep coming,

1:14:34.303 --> 1:14:37.431
but they don't.

1:14:51.737 --> 1:14:54.240
Grandpa, can you help me
with something?

1:14:55.700 --> 1:14:58.327
Anything for you.

1:14:59.161 --> 1:15:02.081
<i>[dance music playing]</i>

1:15:03.457 --> 1:15:04.250
[exhales]

1:15:04.333 --> 1:15:06.544
You really think
he's gonna do it?

1:15:06.627 --> 1:15:09.255
‐He said he would.
‐What if he forgets?

1:15:09.338 --> 1:15:10.256
He was totally lucid
a moment ago.

1:15:10.339 --> 1:15:12.591
It seems really dangerous.

1:15:12.675 --> 1:15:14.010
‐He has Alzheimer's.
‐Do you have a better way

1:15:14.093 --> 1:15:14.552
to sneak out of this wedding?

1:15:14.635 --> 1:15:16.387
We can just walk out.

1:15:16.470 --> 1:15:17.805
She can't, you idiot.
She's the bride.

1:15:17.888 --> 1:15:20.057
[Whitney] Oh, my God, here
he comes. Okay, okay. Um...

1:15:20.141 --> 1:15:21.142
Do we know the plan?
Cake knife?

1:15:21.225 --> 1:15:23.436
‐Check.
‐Platter?

1:15:23.519 --> 1:15:24.937
‐Yeah. Check.
‐Okay.

1:15:32.862 --> 1:15:34.572
Whoa!

1:15:34.655 --> 1:15:36.657
‐[people shouting]
‐Oh, my God. Bruce!

1:15:36.741 --> 1:15:39.243
<i>♪ "She Will Have Her Way"</i>
<i>by Neil Finn ♪</i>

1:15:39.326 --> 1:15:41.829
‐Bruce!
‐[guests screaming]

1:15:41.912 --> 1:15:44.749
‐No! Okay. Go, go, go, go.
‐[laughs] Okay.

1:15:49.170 --> 1:15:50.504
Go find your sister.

1:15:50.588 --> 1:15:51.839
Let's go, let's go, let's go.

1:15:51.922 --> 1:15:53.507
[Colin speaks indistinctly]

1:15:55.593 --> 1:15:56.927
I love you so much.

1:15:59.138 --> 1:16:03.517
<i>♪ I might be old,</i>
<i>but I'm someone new ♪</i>

1:16:03.601 --> 1:16:05.102
<i>♪ She said... ♪</i>

1:16:05.186 --> 1:16:06.437
[Stacey]
I found champagne!

1:16:06.520 --> 1:16:07.396
‐I got the coats!
‐[laughs]

1:16:07.480 --> 1:16:10.316
<i>♪ I could cry always ♪</i>

1:16:10.399 --> 1:16:12.234
<i>♪ In the night</i>
<i>lay your tired arms ♪</i>

1:16:12.318 --> 1:16:16.155
[indistinct chatter]

1:16:16.238 --> 1:16:19.450
<i>♪ She will have her way... ♪</i>

1:16:19.533 --> 1:16:22.203
‐Shh.
‐Are we sure about this?

1:16:22.286 --> 1:16:25.915
<i>♪ Believe her ♪</i>

1:16:25.998 --> 1:16:27.833
Come on.

1:16:27.917 --> 1:16:29.001
[Stacey screams]

1:16:29.085 --> 1:16:31.003
<i>♪ She's the life</i>
<i>I've been frightened of... ♪</i>

1:16:31.087 --> 1:16:34.632
Go, go, go.

1:16:34.715 --> 1:16:39.136
<i>♪ Deathly silence</i>
<i>and especially the dark ♪</i>

1:16:39.220 --> 1:16:42.473
<i>♪ Feels like I am heavy ♪</i>

1:16:42.556 --> 1:16:43.808
<i>♪ And my spirit has died... ♪</i>

1:16:43.891 --> 1:16:45.476
‐Everyone stop! Back up!
‐Whoa...

1:16:45.559 --> 1:16:46.977
‐Back up!
‐Jesus Christ.

1:16:47.061 --> 1:16:48.979
‐What is it?
‐What is going on?

1:16:49.063 --> 1:16:50.981
‐Mom is in there.
‐So?

1:16:52.149 --> 1:16:54.026
Oh, my God.

1:16:54.110 --> 1:16:55.528
Oh, my God.

1:16:55.611 --> 1:16:58.697
[chuckles]
Oh, my God.

1:16:58.781 --> 1:17:00.825
‐Nice.
‐This is so difficult.

1:17:00.908 --> 1:17:02.868
‐What do we do?
‐I don't know, Whit.

1:17:05.538 --> 1:17:07.623
[laughter]

1:17:11.418 --> 1:17:16.006
<i>♪ Do, do, do, do, do, do ♪</i>

1:17:16.090 --> 1:17:18.259
<i>♪ Do, do, do ♪</i>

1:17:18.342 --> 1:17:22.555
<i>♪ Do, do, do, ah‐ah ♪</i>

1:17:22.638 --> 1:17:24.098
<i>♪ Ah‐ah ♪</i>

1:17:24.181 --> 1:17:27.476
<i>♪ Ah ♪</i>

1:17:28.894 --> 1:17:30.813
<i>♪ Still no end in sight ♪</i>

1:17:30.896 --> 1:17:34.191
<i>♪ Though I travel</i>
<i>far and wide ♪</i>

1:17:34.275 --> 1:17:36.277
<i>♪ A dying man</i>
<i>is doing time... ♪</i>

1:17:36.360 --> 1:17:40.197
[Stacey] This is gonna
be a great story.

1:17:40.281 --> 1:17:43.242
<i>♪ She will have her way ♪</i>

1:17:43.325 --> 1:17:45.286
<i>♪ Somehow I will still ♪</i>

1:17:45.369 --> 1:17:49.498
<i>♪ Believe her ♪</i>

1:17:49.582 --> 1:17:54.044
<i>♪ She will have her way ♪</i>

1:17:54.128 --> 1:17:55.671
<i>♪ One day I will ♪</i>

1:17:55.754 --> 1:18:00.384
<i>♪ Come ♪</i>

1:18:00.467 --> 1:18:03.095
<i>♪ Back ♪</i>

1:18:04.346 --> 1:18:07.892
<i>♪ Do, do, do ♪</i>

1:18:07.975 --> 1:18:09.226
<i>♪ Do, do,</i>
<i>do ♪</i>

1:18:09.310 --> 1:18:12.313
<i>♪ Do, do, do ♪</i>

1:18:12.396 --> 1:18:16.025
<i>♪ Do, do,</i>
<i>do ♪</i>

1:18:16.108 --> 1:18:17.818
<i>♪ Do, do, do ♪</i>

1:18:17.902 --> 1:18:22.698
<i>♪ Ah‐ah‐ah‐ah ♪</i>

1:18:24.116 --> 1:18:26.410
<i>♪ Do, do, do ♪</i>

1:18:26.493 --> 1:18:29.163
<i>♪ Do, do,</i>
<i>do ♪</i>

1:18:29.246 --> 1:18:32.041
<i>♪ Do, do, do ♪</i>

1:18:32.124 --> 1:18:34.251
<i>♪ Do, do,</i>
<i>do ♪</i>

1:18:34.335 --> 1:18:37.838
<i>♪ Ah‐ah‐ah‐ah... ♪</i>

1:18:39.715 --> 1:18:43.886
<i>♪ Ah‐ah‐ah‐ah... ♪</i>

1:18:48.307 --> 1:18:51.143
<i>♪ Hey ♪</i>

